Varint (variable-length integer) encoding is a method to encode integers using one or more bytes. Smaller values use fewer bytes. The most common approach is:
- Each byte has 7 bits of data and 1 continuation bit (MSB)
- If the MSB is 1, there are more bytes to follow
- If the MSB is 0, this is the last byte
- The 7 data bits from each byte are combined to form the final value

